<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Grafting Clips for Tomato Seedlings</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Most graft failures aren’t about the cut — they’re about the clip not matching the seedling.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most home gardeners, the best grafting clips for tomato seedlings are soft, flexible clips sized to match the stem diameter at the graft point.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Tomato grafting is relatively forgiving compared to some crops, but clip fit still determines whether the union stays aligned long enough to heal. If the clip is wrong, even a perfect cut can fail.
  </p>
  <p>
    The key is not choosing a “type” of clip — it’s choosing the right size and pressure for the seedlings you actually have.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Works Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> flexible silicone-style clips.</li>
      <li><strong>Best sizing approach:</strong> match clip diameter to stem thickness.</li>
      <li><strong>Best strategy:</strong> keep 2–3 nearby sizes instead of one.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    If you get the size right, most clip styles will work. If you get it wrong, none of them will.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Clip Fit Matters More Than Clip Type</h2>

  <p>
    The clip’s job is simple: hold the scion and rootstock in firm, even contact while they heal. That only works if the pressure is balanced.
  </p>

  <p>
    Too tight, and the stem is crushed or restricted. Too loose, and the graft shifts before the tissues fuse.
  </p>

  <p>
    This balance is what makes sizing more important than material or brand.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Typical Tomato Seedling Sizes at Grafting Stage</h2>

  <p>
    Most tomato seedlings are grafted when stems are still relatively thin and flexible. In many home setups, this falls into a narrow size window — but not a perfectly uniform one.
  </p>

  <p>
    Even small differences in light or watering can create noticeable variation across a tray.
  </p>

  <p>
    That’s why relying on a single clip size often leads to inconsistent results.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Best Clip Types for Tomato Seedlings</h2>

