  <p>
    Flexible clips tend to perform better in typical home conditions where variation is unavoidable.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Choose the Right Size in Practice</h2>

  <p>
    Instead of guessing from a chart, look directly at your seedlings. The clip should fit snugly around the stems without visibly compressing them.
  </p>

  <p>
    A good fit feels stable but not tight. You should not have to force it into place, and it should not wobble once applied.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you’re unsure, having one size slightly smaller and one slightly larger than your “best guess” makes adjustment easier.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where Most Grafting Setups Fail</h2>

  <h3>Using One Clip Size for the Whole Tray</h3>
  <p>
    Even well-grown seedlings vary more than expected.
  </p>

  <h3>Waiting Too Long to Graft</h3>
  <p>
    Stems thicken quickly, making previously correct clips too small.
  </p>

  <h3>Choosing Based on Product Labels</h3>
  <p>
    Clip sizing labels don’t always match real-world stem sizes.
  </p>

  <h3>Applying Too Much Pressure</h3>
  <p>
    More force does not mean better contact — it often means damage.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Clip Choice Interacts With Timing</h2>

  <p>
    Timing and clip size are directly connected. Early grafting favors smaller clips and more delicate handling. Later grafting requires larger clips and introduces more stress on the plant.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your timing is consistent, your clip selection becomes simpler. If your timing varies, you need more flexibility in sizing.
  </p>
</section>

