<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Use</h2>

  <p>
    Use flexible grafting clips in two or three sizes that roughly match your tomato seedlings at graft time. Prioritize fit and gentle pressure over rigid support or exact clip type.
  </p>

  <p>
    This approach handles natural variation and improves consistency without complicating the setup.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Fit the clip to the plant, not the other way around.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best grafting clips for tomato seedlings are those that match stem size closely and apply even, gentle pressure.
  </p>

  <p>
    Flexible clips tend to perform better in home environments, especially when seedlings vary slightly in thickness.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Good fit leads to stable grafts.
  </p>
